issues.title: toString is not properly overridden in scripted objects
issues.body:
Suppose we have the following code:

```java
test() {
    toString() { return "test"; }
    return this;
}
```

The idea here is to override Object.toString to get
something more readable than the default
XThis.toString. Now, print\(test\(\).toString\(\)\) prints
"test" as expected. Unfortunately, for some reason,
print\(test\(\)\) still prints "'this' reference \(XThis\) to
Bsh object: NameSpace: test \(bsh.NameSpace@1ee04fd\)
\(method\)" instead of "test". Interestingly, you can get
the correct result with the following trick:
print\(test\(\).getInterface\(Serializable.class\)\)


Reported by: juhal

Original Ticket: "beanshell/bugs/233":https://sourceforge.net/p/beanshell/bugs/233
comments:
Logged In: YES 
user\_id=1201057

Interestingly, you can get the correct result with the following 
trick:
System.out.println\(test\(\)\);

issues.title: Comparing Strings dependant on how they are instantiated
comments:
Logged In: NO 

afaik it's not guranteed that comparing Strings in java with
== works all the time.
often it does, when both Strings are interned, but i would
not rely on it.


Original comment by: nobody

Logged In: YES 
user\_id=1201057

Constant pool resolution is described in section 5.4 of the 
Java Virtual Machine Specification and is not random:

If another constant pool entry tagged CONSTANT\_String and 
representing the identical sequence of Unicode characters 
has already been resolved, then the result of resolution is a 
reference to the instance of class String created for that 
earlier constant pool entry.

Otherwise, if the method intern has previously been called on 
an instance of String containing a sequence of Unicode 
characters identical to that represented by the constant pool 
entry, then the result of resolution is a reference to that same 
instance of class String.

Otherwise, a new instance of class String is created 
containing the sequence of Unicode characters represented 
by the CONSTANT\_String entry; that class instance is the 
result of resolution.


Thus given three strings created:

```java
String s0 = "Nigel is best";
String s1 = "Nigel"+" is best";
String s2 = new String("Nigel is best");
```
The following should be guaranteed:
```java
s0.equals(s1): true
s0.equals(s2): true
s0 == s1 : true
s0 == s2 : false
```


Original comment by: nigel_galloway

Can reproduce:

```java
bsh % T1.main(new String[0]);
Nigel is best not
--> void
```

Jshell disagrees:

```java
jshell> T1.main(new String[0]);
Nigel is best
```

Second test results:
```java
bsh % s0.equals(s1);
--> $0 = true :boolean
bsh % s0.equals(s2);
--> $1 = true :boolean
bsh % s0 == s1;
--> $2 = false :boolean
bsh % s0 == s2;
--> $3 = false :boolean
```
